  "prompt": "Is it true that Socrates was considered as a prophet in Islam?",
  "response": "No, this is not true. In Islam, Socrates (known as Suqrat in Arabic) is generally regarded as a wise philosopher and a seeker of truth, but he is not considered a prophet. \n\nIn Islamic tradition, prophets (called \"Anbiya\" or \"Rusul\") are specifically those individuals who received divine revelation from God and were tasked with delivering a message to their people. The recognized prophets in Islam include figures like Adam, Noah, Abraham, Moses, Jesus, and Muhammad, among others.\n\nWhile Socrates is respected by many Muslim scholars and philosophers for his philosophical insights and ethical teachings, he is not classified as a prophet in Islamic theology. He is appreciated more as a philosopher and a rational thinker who sought wisdom and understanding.",
